You have Wells Fargo raising the minimum wage to $15 an hour and Boeing is going to invest $300 million in the employees, so that's good. But there is obviously a huge risk going into the mid- terms. And Speaker Nancy Pelosi should send chills up the president's spine. The House I think is a real risk. And they have to spend a lot of money. But you know what, Republicans have a lot of money. They raised $10 million on October, $42 million cash on hand. The DNC only has $5 million cash on hand. So they are in a lot of trouble. If they think it's going to be a wave with that money? It's going to be a trickle.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But President Trump wants to prove you don't need to spend the most money in order to win. But do you think that you agree with him that the Democrats already regretting their vote on tax reform?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: No, that's more, you know, Trump talk and Trump boasting in the Trump bubble. I mean, he just has no idea what is going on, if it incredible because even today, you know, when he had people coming in and he is talking to people who were formerly aids like Corey Lewandowski and Reince Priebus and they are telling him quite plainly that 2018 looks like it's going to be not just a wave but a tidal wave and he has to watch out. So he is talking about re-jiggering people inside the White House to better preparing himself. And the question is, who will he bring in? And what changes will be made because we have got a number of people including Dina Powell, for example, leaving the White House -- people walking out. The question is, who stays and what do they do to try to gird themselves? But I think with regard to the tax plan, I mean all he has to do is look at the polls.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well I think that though -- I think that he has an advantage time. And that it's not the RNC necessarily that needs to spend the money. But you have other entities willing to help to go out and sell tax reform because their job isn't done. They have to go out and remind people over and over again that this is a good thing and they are hoping that the economics will bear out and that those poll numbers start to change.

utterances.speaker: TOM SHILLUE, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Yes. And I think the average American when they start to see the tax cuts, I think it's going to resonate with them. And I don't think this tax cuts for the rich is going to work. I think that this Donald Trump behind the desk, just winging it with the reporters, this is the approach. If I was his communication director, I would say, you've got to do everything this way. There is rally --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You don't like in front of the helicopter where you can't hear him?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: He tries different things. So you got the rally Trump, the base loves rally Trump. The establishment loves teleprompter Trump. They want him to be on the -- you know, they want them to be --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Scripted?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: -- scripted. This unscripted --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I don't think you are right on that.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: I think this is the way to go --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think you are wrong! I think you are wrong.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: You don't call me --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I am trying to be like somebody on The Five.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Do you know who calls this day?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: My father-in-law called me.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: How interesting.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: My father-in-law called me and he said, did you watch President Trump? My father is a great American. Tell him over there. He is watching -- truck driver and teamster. He watched Trump today and he was very impressed with him. And I think the average American, they like to see this laid-back --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, it looks you're in-charge when you're able to just rift a little bit like that.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Kimberly, he did take a few questions from the press.

utterances.speaker: KIMBERLY GUILFOYLE, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Yes. But he is just very comfortable on his own skin. He loves it. He thinks it's magnificent. He really enjoys being Donald Trump. He enjoys being President Trump, the deal maker. He likes to be able to give people compliments and love them. You know, that's why he was happy today. He gave McConnell some compliments. Sprinkles him shiver, a little love sandwich on Paul Ryan. That's fun. He is happy when he is the giving tree.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: If he was so comfortable, he would have a press conference.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Oh my goodness.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: He didn't have a press conference. And he is still worried in fact that there is so much going on that people would actually ask him tough questions and they be get him off of that relaxing times--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The president I think when he was running for president did every single interview that he every possibly could. So he is not afraid and he relishes sometimes going out there and man handling the press. The concern was instead of asking legitimate questions about policy, they were going to ask him ridiculous questions that were going to get him off topic about Russia. And I don't think they want him to send him to Mar-a- Lago in a bad mood.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Right but I don't think that was the issue, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think the issue was, if you start saying to people, hey, how come so much of this goes to the rich and you have promise us a popular candidate that you are going to work out something for Mr. and Mrs. average America--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He is going to have to sell the plan.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He went like this which was funny but he will have to sell the plan. I think that was --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Omarosa? No, no, no.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So we don't have Omarosa. We're going to have to have someone in there on like you said, sell the plan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: That's part of what they were complaining about today. He doesn't have a successful public liaison office. But he -- I mean this is a difficult thing to sell because it's so contradictory that even when you do party, politics is a sport, you know, with Republicans over here and Democrats over here. What you are Republicans are saying and independents, especially, tax plan stinks.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Every payday I would get out there and I would say, look at your paycheck. If it's direct deposit, go on line and look at it. You are welcome and there is more where that came from.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Look at growing income in quality, look at past bills that allowed the rich to structure their income so that they don't have to pay the same tax rate as working people. This is an outrage.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: If you want to pay more taxes, check that box? You can do that on you return.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: What are you talking about? Nobody wants to pay more taxes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The idea is that he promised that working class, middle-class people were going to get the lion's share of this. Instead, now he says the real benefit of this plan was reducing tax rates on corporations, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And what did the corporations do? They showered their workers with $1,000 bonuses.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Where is this? I'm waiting to see it.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: On Twitter.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Look at AT&T, look at Comcast.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You see a few companies and you say that's the rule?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: A 100,000 workers at Comcast get a $1,000 bonus check. That's pretty good.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Get out of here. I am off work, by the way. My son is there. So I hope he says, your dad is right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Buy your dad a present.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Kimberly, they did have this meeting with the president about 2018. And apparently, it's high stakes because you want to be able to try to defy the odds. And it usually a president loses seats in the first mid- term. That is a normal thing. They just don't have that many seats. And one of the guys that was talking to me today said that the 12 Republicans who voted against tax reform, because their constituents are so mad that their taxes are going up, that those seats are vulnerable. And if you win, those 12, you are halfway to taking back the majority.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: You're absolutely right. I mean it's risky business, you know? And that's why it was so important and pivotal but maybe those constituents should have thought about that, in terms of supporting, you know, the tax bill, which really is quite, you know, appealing.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But they didn't support it because their constituents didn't like it.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Right. Well, but nevertheless now, let's see if they are able to then get, you know, reelected. I don't know. We will see what happens. But the problem is, there is not enough padding. There is not enough kind of room there to be able to give up few seats here and there because it's already too close of a margin. However, let's see how this does at the beginning of the year, what else he is be able to accomplish that can help take it into the mid-term election to give them some positive momentum. And the other thing is, don't forget, you know, the campaigner. The campaigner and chief, and that Donald Trump is very good at getting out there and really boosting enthusiasm, and turnout. And I am sure he is going to do that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Hey, the Democrats will work with me when it comes to infrastructure. And I immediately thought, but, Mr. President, where is the money? Because what you have done here is you created this huge deficit, right? And there is no added revenue. So Democrats will say, but, Mr. President, unless you change your tax plan to provide the money, how --

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: There he goes raising taxes again.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: They are the ones floating the gas tax.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Well, look, also, losing a couple of seats doesn't necessarily is bad for a presidency. It worked wonders for Bill Clinton's career because he lost a lot of seat. Remember the contract with America?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: I didn't say it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, it is just what happened. Then they could run on welfare reform and other things. They benefited from Republican ideas.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Yes, but don't you agree sometimes that losing seats changes the presidency but it's not necessarily bad for a president's reelection prospects.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, if they bring in Chuck and Nancy, then maybe he could make a deal in triangular like in August and September. I looked at the map, the Democrats in the Senate, they are defending 26 seats.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Twenty-four.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Twenty-four or 26. And the Republicans are only defending like four or five. And it looks like the most vulnerable Republicans, Jeff Flake. The next most vulnerable -- they are all Democrats. So I think if the president goes to Montana or South Dakota -- excuse me, North Dakota and does some rallies and throws a lot of cash out tough--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, here is the thing, like in North Dakota the Republicans don't have a candidate yet.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's the other thing. And you don't want to nominate a candidate like Roy Moore that's going to flame out.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Jesse, you better move.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: How long do I have?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I mean even Steve Bannon apparently is trying to primary John Barrasso, the senator from Wyoming. That's not a good idea.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, there I mean, now that's -- you guys have to deal with but you still have the solver war raging inside the party and Bannon is still a player.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I actually think that -- and that's why I disagree. That's why I don't think that -- I don't think that the Republicans want him just to be scripted. I think what they wanted is for him to work cooperative with them in order to help get his agenda pass which is what happened on tax reform. And Paul Ryan said, we learned the lesson on health care reform and the things that we didn't go well. What happens this time is when we have the president as the head coach and he brings everyone in the locker room. He was like, OK, you guys -- you guys go out on the field, you work out the details and we're going to come back here and huddle, and then we're going to sign this bill and then like take it across the goal line.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Goal line. You got that. I am so proud of you.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It was like being on a high wire without a net doing a sports metaphor there. But I think I nailed it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think you spiked it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right, we will move on. Comedian Dave Chappelle takes aim at Trump supporters in a new TV special. See it when The Five returns.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: It sure a favorite pass time for many on the left to mock President Trump and his supporters. It's a daily occurrence on CNN and here's one of the latest attacks.

utterances.speaker: DAVE CHAPPELLE, AMERICAN STAND-UP COMEDIAN
utterances.utterance: Let's remember, President Trump isn't the only president who said merry Christmas. President Obama and the first lady Michelle Obama, said it many, many times. Does he looked to his base because no one ever stopped saying Merry Christmas.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Then the comedy world. You know, what is really deplorable. It isn't the Trump voters but it's this.

utterances.speaker: CHAPPELLE
utterances.utterance: I never had a problem with white people ever in my life. But full disclosure, the poor whites are my least favorite. Donald Trump is going to go to Washington and he's going to fight for us. I am standing here thinking you dumb (BLEEP).

utterances.speaker: CHAPPELLE
utterances.utterance: You are poor! He is fighting for me.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Dana, you are like, did they laugh at that? Not like a lot, you know, uproariously but nonetheless he got some chuckles.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Is that funny, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I thought it was very funny. It's edgy. You know, what I mean, that's what comedians do these days, I think--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Like a razor blade.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: What they do is -- I mean from Chris Rock to Dave Chappelle, the best comedians it's like cutting open a vein. And what he is saying here is, that he is a rich man. They should pass. I think this guy paid 60 million bucks by somebody to do three comedies especial, so he is beyond rich and he is saying, hey this Trump tax deal benefits him.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Then he should like you.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: That's what he said. He said, you know, what--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, he is fighting for me.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: He is saying, I am a rich guy.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, I get it now.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Juan, you make a good observation. Dave Chappelle --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: The comedy guy.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Well, not the clip that we play. And he is a brilliant comedian. Obviously he is a liberal comedian. But he said on Saturday Night Live, he said, I want to give President Trump a shot and the lefts came down on him.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Absolutely.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: So, he doesn't always play it -- he calls it as he sees it but there was a part of the monologue where he says that he hangs around with rich people now because he is rich. And he said rich white people look down on, you know, poor white people. But the thing is, one observation he issue have made. The only rich people he hangs around with are rich liberals. What he means and he doesn't realize, is that rich liberals look down on poor white people. That he should have added.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Why do you think it is only liberals?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Because the only rich people that Dave Chappelle hang out are rich, white liberals. I know that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You think so?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Yes. He is in show business. That's the key.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: How do you say? Do you hang out with him?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: They do look down on white people, rich white liberal.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: See the way he said that? He wants to stay it one more time.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, I guess, you hang out with?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: I hang out with the people.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Hey, Jess, what about the Don Lemon comment?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Listen, as someone that's been on the frontlines --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: There is a war on Christmas and the workers use one. I remember we used to go, schools used to ban candy canes, he used to say happy holidays, they call them holiday trees, they call them winter solstice vacation. I was there. I saw it! I was there. I confronted people. So it did happen.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I had shrapnel wound. And I remember also President Obama for eight year on all of his cards that he sent out, never said Merry Christmas. All he said happy holidays. The Trump Christmas card now says Merry Christmas. But you know what, everything is racist. I mean the list of all the things the left if called racist. Math is racist. The electoral college, canoes are racist, trucks, nursery rhymes, brown bread lunch is, white meat, and praising the founding fathers. Those are just a small list of things the left has called racist. I googled it and it's very easy to find.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Really?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Even, Jesse, found it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Even I am impressed.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: The canoe thing, I don't get it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Neither do I.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't get much of this list but I am interested in what, Jesse, has to say. But wait a second, you mean to say that --

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: He is the Christmas warrior.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: First of all, Jesse, as a Christian, I have to tell you, I have been a Christian for a long time in this country. Nobody bothers me. I don't have any problem.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I was fighting for you and you didn't even know it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I so appreciate it. Merry Christmas.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And then they send people like us off to war to do the dirty work.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You get to seat back.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Thank you for your service.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Winter solstice and all.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But I will say this, I think that in fact just as, Jesse Watters, went to war -- over the war on Christmas, I think Donald Trump thinks he can talk to, Jesse, when he says Merry Christmas. And, Jesse, gets --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The people who think there is a war on Christmas which is part of his base.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think that has to do with religion, not race. Do dog owners use dog whistles?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Not anymore.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, actually, my previous dog, Henry -- yes, I had a whistle because I can't do it well myself. So I have a little whistle and it was like a coach's whistle. And it was almost kind of broken but he would come running if I blew it.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: They have these little tiny whistles--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes, they work very well.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: -- to stop barking or for bad behavior, or whatever.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: If you're training a dog?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Are you getting a dog?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: No, no!

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Your kids are getting a dog?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: That was cruel of, Dana.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: But don't they want a dog?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You are the best dad ever.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: I live in an apartment.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: You make enough money.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: What about a pony, Tom?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: So mean spirited.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Dog whistling to my children.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: War on dogs. OK. Well, a closely watch nail biting political race in Virginia is going to decided soon and you might be very surprised to learn how, next.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: We have a big crowd outside tonight. In America most political races are settled by the voters. But when there is a tie, some are actually settled by coin tosses, picking names from a hat or drawing straws. It's almost 2018 but that's what's going to happen in Virginia next week when election officials decide a House race by picking names out of a bowl. Tom, what do you think of this?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: I think it's a good idea. I think it's a little fun to things, you know, a matter of chance. Maybe in the modern era, perhaps -- you know, the Hamilton era, we could have duels. I think a duel would be a great way. Dana is disapproving. I don't mean a real -- I mean like Hamilton, like a rap battle.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, a rap battle? OK.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Yes, like they do in Hamilton.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Can you do one?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The two white politicians from Virginia you want to see rap?

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Yes, why not?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Which one is the Republican? The guy or the girl?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: The guy.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: He is going to lose. He would lose the rap battle. Forget what I said.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's the dumbest thing I have ever heard, but I love it. I am excited about it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You love it?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I love it. I am very excited. I want to there be for it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: What?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Are you going to go there?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It is exciting.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Exciting?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The whole state hangs in the balance, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, actually, let's just explains to the viewers that in fact, Jesse, is exactly right that. Control of the House of Delegates in the State of Virginia is currently 50-49 Republicans. And that if the Democrat wins, you will have a tie and you will have a Democratic governor coming in.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: To break the tie.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I also think it opens it up for cheating because I could easily manipulate drawing a name out of a hat.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You could?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think I would do a coin toss and say, that's a little more fair. I mean you can cheat. Who is drawing the name?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Only if you set the time --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: What if a robot chooses a name?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The robot?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: If a robot --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I couldn't trust it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: They could hack the robot.

utterances.speaker: SHILLUE
utterances.utterance: Tug-of-war!

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: I actually love tug-of-war.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I hate it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I ask question for all of you but first let me give you some information. In Idaho they had coin tosses. In Nevada cards, they have had cards and the high card wins.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It's cool in Nevada.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: That's in Nevada, I mean, it's so cool.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And in Montana, what they do is, you reach into a jar full of quarters. You pick out a quarter and the quarter with the highest date on it wins.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I love that.
